HW2-part2- Feature engineering

Sinja Sharma

strk <- read.csv("https://sin-ja.github.io/STA552/Project1/stroke-data.csv")

1 Introduction to Feature Engineering

Feature engineering is an important step in data processing that transforms raw data into meaningful features to improve model performance. Based on the exploratory data analysis performed before, several key patterns have been observed that could inform the feature engineering tasks. These patterns include a skewness of the response variable “stroke” and some numerical variables, imbalance in categorical variables, and the presence of some redundant or highly correlated feature variables. Feature transformation techniques will be applied to correct the skewness in highly skewed numerical variables. Next, feature selection will be conducted to filter out low variance features, and multicollinearity. Finally, feature creation will introduce new variables that helps in identifying underlying patterns observed in EDA.

1.1 Feature Transforming

# to identify skewed variables 
num_vars <- strk%>% select(where(is.numeric))
skewness_val <- sapply(num_vars, skewness, na.rm = TRUE) # calculate skewness for each numeric variable
high_skew <- names(skewness_val[abs(skewness_val) > 1])
print(high_skew)
[1] "hypertension"      "heart_disease"     "avg_glucose_level"
[4] "stroke"           
# box-cox transformation 
strk <- strk %>% 
  mutate(across(all_of(high_skew), ~ caret::BoxCoxTrans(.)$x.t, .names = "boxcox_{.col}"))
# min-max normalization 
preproc_minmax <- preProcess(num_vars, method = "range")
strk_scaled <- predict(preproc_minmax, num_vars)

# standardization (mean=0, SD=1)
preproc_std <- preProcess(num_vars, method = "center","scale")
strk_std <- predict(preproc_std, num_vars)

1.3 Feature Creation

Feature creation is a crucial step in preparing data for machine learning models by creating new, meaningful varaibles in the dataset. Based on the EDA, model performance can be enhanced by category regrouping, discretization, model-based feature engineering, Principal Component Analysis (PCA).

2 Category Regrouping

Some categorical variables in the original dataset were imbalanced can reduce stability of the model.

3 Discretization of Multi-modal Variables

Some continous variables exhibit multi-modal distributions which makes it difficult to interpret them. Variables such as BMI and age were conerted into bins or categories such as “Child”. “Young adult”, “Middle age”, “Senior”, and “Elderly”. to better reflect risk for stroke in different groups and improve interpretabiltiy.

4 Feature Engineering with Model-Based Methods

Model based feature creation can extract hidden patterns in the data. Clustering groups individuals with similar characteristics into clusters. K-means application to numeric variables such as age, and BMI creates a new risk cluster variable to differentiate groups with different stroke probabilities.

5 PCA

Principal Component Analysis (PCA) transforms correlated features into smaller uncorrelated components, thereby preserving the most significant variance. PCA is applied to selected numeric variables to reduce dimensionality to improve model performance.

PC1 (Dim1) explains 32.43% of the total variance PC1 + PC2 explain 52.43% of variance, meaning they contain the majority of the information. PC1 and PC4 capture 85% of the variance. PC1(Dim1) is strongly influenced by age (34.3%), hypertension(22.4%), and glucose level (22.6%). PC3(Dim3) is influenced by hypertension (43.65%) and heart_diease (55.84%). PC2 (Dim2) is ID so should be ignored in further analysis.

# create clusters with K-means 
set.seed(123)
kmeans_model <- kmeans(num_vars, centers = 3) # apply k-means clustering (3 clusters)
strk$cluster <- as.factor(kmeans_model$cluster) # add cluster labels to dataset
